Getting started in R

1. Using R as a calculator (arithmetic operators)

The simplest thing you can do with R is arithmetic operations, similar to Python:

1 + 100    
## [1] 101

You can use any other arithmetic operation such as:

  • Add (sum)
  • Subtract
  • Multiply
  • Divide
  • Exponents
  • Brackets / parentheses

Evaluate these operations:

2 * 3 + 5
2 * (3 + 5)

See help(Arithmetic) or ?Arithmetic to check the main arithmetic operations

2. Assignment of variables

a <- 1 + 2
a = 1 + 2 # "<-" and "=" are the same thing
b = 2 + 1

Notice that assignment does not print any value, but you can always print them using print(a)

3. Other useful and common numeric commands/functions

# Get the absolute value
abs(-2)
# Square root of any value
sqrt(4)
# natural logarithm
x <- 4
log(x)
# Common logarithm
log10(x); log(x = x, base = 10 ) # you can use ; to separte line of code
# Antilog 
10^log(x, 10)
# Round a number with 2 decimals
round(3.475, digits=2)
# Round a number with 1 decimals
round(3.475, digits=1)

4. Comparisons

1 + 2 == 2 + 1

a = 1 + 2 
b = 2 + 1

# a == b is the same but using variables instead
a == b

# you can also ask whether they are different
a != b

Check when object less or greater than:

a < b

# What does "b" represent after running this?
b <- b + 1

a < b

See help(Comparison) or ?Comparison to check the main arithmetic operations

5. The Workspace in R

The workspace is your current R working environment and includes any user-defined objects (vectors, matrices, data frames, lists, functions). At the end of an R session, the user can save an image of the current workspace which is automatically reloaded the next time that R is initialized. Commands are entered interactively at the R user prompt. Up and down arrow keys scroll through your command history.

The ls function shows all the objects in your workspace:

ls()

5.1. The current working directory

The working directory is the local folder at your PC that will be used for reading or saving any file in R by default.

To check which is our Current Working Directory (CWD) use:

getwd()

You can always change your working directory:

setwd("/Users/mydirectory")  # change to mydirectory

5.2. Save your workspace and continue later

You can save your workspace in the file .RData in the cwd using:

mio <- c("a","b","c")
save.image()

Alternatively, you can save specific objects to a file, if you dont specify the path, the cwd is assumed

save(mio, file="my_R_objects.RData")

If you want to continue you can load a workspace into the current session and again if you dont specify the path, the cwd is assumed

load("my_R_objects.RData")

5.3. History of used commands

You can easily recover several R commands that were used previously:

history()

5.4. Leaving R

Note: You will be prompted to save the workspace.

q()

6. Basic type of data structure

Understanding data structure is very important because you will use them on a day-to-day basis in R programing and routines, and it uses to be one of the most common source of frustration among beginners. Consider that everything in R will be an R-object and some of them would be very basic (i.e.vectors) but others quite complexes.

There are 4 basic atomic classes:

  1. logical (e.g., TRUE, FALSE)
  2. integer (e.g., 2L) Note: Using L suffix, you get an integer rather than a numeric
  3. numeric (real or decimal) (e.g, 2, 2.0, pi)
  4. character (e.g, a, swc, the book), can be also called string

In R there are 5 main data structures that will review each of those data structure to understand their uses and other more complex objects:

  1. Vector
  2. Matrix
  3. Data frame
  4. List (Its a vector where any element is of any kind)
  5. Array (we will avoid them, but they have several uses)
  6. Others are complex objects (i.e.SummarizedExperiment):

6.1. VECTOR

A vector is the most common and basic data structure in R and is pretty much the workhorse of R. There are four common types of atomic vectors: logical, integer, numeric (often called double), and character.

You can create a vector with multiple values into an object using c(), this will make a vector with a length of n elements in the vector.

x.num <- c(1,2,3,4,5)
# Make a sequence
x.num <- c(1:5)
print(x.num) # We should print because assignmetns do not print values

# With the L suffix, to get integer
x.int <- c(1L,2L,3L,4L,5L)
print(x.int)

x.char <- c("Fiat","Opel","VW","BMW","Mercedes AMG")
print(x.char)

# Use TRUE and FALSE (or T and F) to create logical vectors
x.log <- c(TRUE,TRUE,FALSE,T,F)
print(x.log)

You can do many things with a vector:

print(x.num)

Get the maximal or minimal value within a vector, or even to operate with them:

max(x.num)
min(x.num)

# Divide each value by 10
res.x.num <- x.num/10
print(res.x.num)

# Mean value
mean(x.num)

# The sum of all values within the vector
sum(x.num)

You can also create sequence of numbers:

my.object <- seq(from = 1, to = 22, by = 1)
# Another way to do the same thing:
my.object <- 1:22

It is also very common combine a vector with other values or vectors:

res.x.num <- c(x.num, 1000)
print(res.x.num)

res.x.num <- c(x.num, my.object)
print(res.x.num)

You can refer (index) to elements of a vector using a numeric vector of positions within brackets.

x.num[4]
x.log[c(1,3,5)]
x.char[2:4]

6.2. MATRICES

A matrix is a R object where elements are arranged in a two-dimensional layout. Matrices contain element of the same data type (numeric, character, or logical). Matrices are created with the matrix() function. General structure of a matrix: matrix[rows, columns] How to build a matrix? help(matrix)

# Create 2x2 matrix from a vector
vector <-c(1,2,3,4)
foo <- matrix(data = vector,
             nrow=2,
             ncol=2)
print(foo)
# Create 5 x 4 matrix
foo <- matrix(data = 1:20,
             nrow=5,
             ncol=4,
             byrow = TRUE) # We know the vector will fill each column.
print(foo)
# Create 2x2 matrix with row and column names
vector <-c(1,2,3,4)
foo <- matrix(data = vector,
             nrow=2,
             ncol=2,
             dimnames = list(c("gene1","gene2"),c("sample1","sample2")))
print(foo)

You can identify rows, columns, or elements of a matrix, x, by using subscripts and brackets.

  • x[i,] refers to the ith row
  • x[,j] refers to jth column
  • x[i,j] refers to the i,jth element
# Create 2x2 matrix with row and column names
x <- matrix(1:10, nrow=2)
print(x)
# the 2nd row and all columns
x[2,]

# the 2nd column and all rows
x[,2]

# the 1st row and 4th column
x[1,4]

# the 1st row and 4th and 5th columns
x[1, c(4,5)]

# by row name and column name
foo["gene1", ]

foo[,"sample2"]

6.3. DATA FRAME

A data frame is more general than a matrix in that different columns can contain different modes of data (numeric, character, etc.). A data frame is created with the data.frame() function

Each column must have only one data type, but you can put columns of different data types together to form the data frame. Because data frames are close to what analysts typically think of as datasets, well use the terms columns and variables interchangeably when discussing data frames.

# Create a data frame or table
df <- data.frame(Student = c("Maria","Jose","Ana","Marta","Juan"),
                 Pass = c(T,F,F,T,T), 
                 Attendance= c(100,80,90,100,100))

print(df)

Usually data frames are created from tabulated tables, so this is a very common method to load datasets into our workspace.

# Make a data frame from a table in a tabulated file
gencode <- read.table(file = "gencode_GRCh38.txt", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
print(head(gencode))

Alternatively you can load the tabulated file from an url, you can use both methods to load gencode in your workspace.

# Make a data frame from a table in URL


gencode <- read.table("https://www.dropbox.com/s/le9vs2n51lsxlw1/gencode_GRCh38.txt?dl=1",
                       header=TRUE,
                       stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

You should always have a quick look to data frame contents:

# Class of elements in gencode
str(gencode)

# Summary of its information 
summary(gencode)

# Count type of repeated elements in a column /vector
table(gencode$chromosome)
table(gencode$type)

# Make a table combining the type of genes and chromosome location
table(gencode$type,gencode$chromosome)

You can also explore specific data vectors or positions into the data.frame using index.

# All the information of the gene in the 20th row
gencode[20, ]
# All the information of the gene in the 20th row and 3rd column
gencode[20, 3]

8. Subsetting data frames

8.1. Subsetting using subset

# Get rows where gene_name column is == to "GLI2"
subset(gencode, gene_name=="GLI2")

# Get rows where gene_name column has == to "GLI2"
subset(gencode, gene_name%in%c("GLI2","HLF"))

# Select genes in Chromosome 21
gencode.21 <- subset(gencode, chromosome=="chr21")

8.2. Subsetting using which

The command which detect the index of elements matching a logical comparison.

# See the row number of genes located in the mitochondrial chromosome"
which(gencode$chromosome=="chrM")

# Subset the data frame and keep it in a object named gencode.mt
gencode.mt <- gencode[which(gencode$chromosome=="chrM"), ]

# It is also possible to make in this way:
gencode.mt <- gencode[gencode$chromosome=="chrM", ]

# To check the number of genes that in this case match with the number of row.
nrow(gencode.mt)

9. Control strutures:

9.1. Control strutures: if"

Syntax: if (Condition 1=TRUE) { Command 1 }

a=3
b=2

if(a > b){
  print("b is less than a")
}

9.2. Control strutures: if-else

Syntax: if (Condition 1=TRUE) { Command 1 } else { Command 2}

if(a > b){
  print("b is less than a")
}else{
    print("b is not less than a")
}

9.3. Control strutures: if-else"

x.num <- c(1:5)
print(x.num)
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5
ifelse(test = x.num==3, yes = TRUE, no = FALSE)
ifelse(test = x.num==3, yes = 1, no = 0 )

# The syntax is semi-automatic by the order of elements.
ifelse(x.num==3, "black", "red")
color.result <- ifelse(x.num==3, "black", "red")

9.4. Control strutures: for

for(i in x.num){
  print(i)
}

Here we use color.result after using ifelse on x.num to analyse which value will be in each step.

for(i in x.num){
  print(paste("The number",i,"is the color", color.result[i], sep=" "))

}

10. Plots

Load again the file with gencode data. Here you have a summary of the main graphical parameters. 
gencode <- read.table("https://www.dropbox.com/s/le9vs2n51lsxlw1/gencode_GRCh38.txt?dl=1", 
                      header=TRUE, 
                      stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

10.1. Scatter plot

Dot plots can be made with two numeric vectors of elements. Here we will use the index of the genes (order of the genes) in the chromosome with respect to the genomic coordinates of its start site independently of their strand orientation.

gencode.7 <- subset(gencode, chromosome=="chr7")
gencode.7$position <- gencode.7$start + (gencode.7$end - gencode.7$start)

plot(x = gencode.7$position/1E6,
     y = length(gencode.7$position):1,
     col=ifelse(gencode.7$type=="miRNA","red","grey"),
     cex=ifelse(gencode.7$type=="miRNA",0.5,0.1),
     main="miRNA position",
     xlab="Genome position (Mbases)",
     ylab="Gene index")
abline(v=60)

10.2. Histogram

Histograms are useful to explore the distribution of a set of values.

hist(x = (gencode$end - gencode$start),
     xlab="Gene length",
     main = "Gene length distribution",
     col="blue",
     breaks = 20 )

Now we will repeat the same histogram but scaling the gene length for base 10 logarithm.

10.3. Density plot

gene.length.density <- density(x = log10(gencode$end - gencode$start) , bw = 0.1)
# Have a look the structure of the density object
class(gene.length.density)
str(gene.length.density)
# The density object can be directly used for plot
plot(x = gene.length.density,
     xlab="Gene length",
     main = "Gene length distribution",
     col="blue")

Training exercise: Repeat the density function plot using multiple different bandwidth values. Does the curve change?

Now, we will compare two distributions within the same plot.

gencode.PC <- subset(gencode, type=="protein_coding")

gene.length.density.PC <- density(x = log10(gencode.PC$end - gencode.PC$start) , bw = 0.1)

plot(x = gene.length.density,
     xlab="Gene length",
     main = "Gene length distributions",
     col="blue",
     xlim=c(0,7),
     ylim=c(0,0.7))

lines(gene.length.density.PC,
      col="red",
      lwd=3)

10.4. Bar plots (Bar charts)

Calculate the number of genes per biotype and make a vector keeping only those gene biotypes with more than 300 genes. Sort the vector and assign the result into the object titled: table.gencode.300.sorted

# Makes the table of number of genes per type
table.gencode = table(gencode$type)

# Use "which" you can select those that match your comparison
table.gencode.300 <- table.gencode[which(table.gencode > 300)]

# Sort the table from higher to lower number of genes (decreasing)
table.gencode.300.sorted  <- sort(table.gencode.300)

Visit Gencode website to understand the meaning of gene biotypes (link).

# The bar plot is useful to represent the quantitative value of different categories.
barplot(table.gencode.300.sorted,
        horiz = T, # this argument makes the bar plot horizontal
        las=1, # this argument makes the axis names horizontal
        cex.names = 0.55) # this argument reduce the font size of the axis labels

10.5. Box plots

This is an important plot used for comparing distributions across different classes (or categories). Usually the default box-and-whisker plot allows us to explore the median as well as the 1st and 3rd quartile, this also helps to check wheter there are values that might be outliers.

# Subset gencode to keep only the most frequent byotypes
selected.gencode <- subset(gencode, type%in%names(table.gencode.300.sorted))

# Here we are adding a column with a new variable
# Please, note that the gencode object is going to be modified.
selected.gencode$length <- (selected.gencode$end-selected.gencode$start)
selected.gencode$log10length <-  log10(selected.gencode$length)

# We can make a formula to represent the relationship between two variables.
boxplot(formula=log10length~type,
        data=selected.gencode,
        horizontal=TRUE,
        las=1,
        cex.axis=0.8,
        col="lightblue",
     xlab="Gene length (log10)",
     main = "Length distribution by Gene Biotype",
     varwidth = FALSE)

10.7. Saving plots as PDF

Its good to save your plots in a figure folder.

gencode.1 <- subset(gencode, chromosome=="chr1")

# We have to switch-on the graphical device to save the plot into a pdf file.
pdf(file = "Figure_scatter_plot_length_log10_vs_position.pdf", width = 5, height = 5)
plot(x = gencode.1$start/1E6,
     y= gencode.1$log10length)
# We have to switch-off the graphical device and makes the output.
dev.off()

If you are interested on more details about graphical paramenters visit in Quick-R website > Advanced Graphs > Graphical Parameters. For instance, check how to use Triangle symbols instead of circles.

11. Combining and merging data frames

11.1. Combine data frames by row or columns

By rows:

# Make and object for genes in chromosome 1
gencode.1 <- subset(gencode, chromosome=="chr1")
# Make and object for genes in chromosome 2
gencode.2 <- subset(gencode, chromosome=="chr2")
# Joint and make a data frame combining genes from chr1 and chr2
gencode.1.2 <- rbind(gencode.1,  gencode.2)

By columns:

# Make and object for gene positions
gencode.position <- gencode[1:1000,c("gene_id","chromosome","start","strand")]
# Make and object for gene bio types
gencode.biotypes <- gencode[1:1000,c("gene_name","type")]
# Joint and make a data frame with genes for chr1 and chr2
gencode.1000<- cbind(gencode.position,  gencode.biotypes)

11.2. Merging data frames by using a common variable

Imaging that you have two different data frames with information related to genes, such as their positions in the genome and another data frame with information abouth the GC content of genes.

If you upload the file gencode_v29_Gene_GC_contents.txt into RStudio cloud you can use this command: gene.gc.content <- read.table(file = "gencode_v29_Gene_GC_contents.txt", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

Alternatively, you can also use the provided dropbox link to directly download this file:

merged.genes.gc <- merge(x = gencode, y = gene.gc.content, by.x="gene_id", by.y="ensembl_gene_id")
